Last week I was in @YellowstoneNPS learning about some of the effects of climate change on the park and our natural resources. Right now I’m in a hearing in DC on the macroeconomic and national security impacts of climate change. This is not a drill. We need to act. pic.twitter.com/EN9KzUmAcz

"Climate change is real. Industrial activity around the globe is the dominant contributor. And the challenge it poses to society merits significant action at every level of government and the private sector."

- Rich Powell, executive director of conservative group ClearPath

"Highly globalized sectors will feel repercussions from shifts in consumer behavior and regulations oceans away. Major U.S. industries will be affected."

- Alicia Seiger, Managing Director of Stanford's Sustainable Finance Initiative, on the transition impacts of climate change

"We cannot separate our national security from our natural security."

- Andy Karsner, venture capitalist, entrepreneur, board member at Conservation International

"Risk management is as important for the military as it is for banking. We can't afford to ignore the risks of climate change, just as bankers can't afford to ignore the risks to their business."

- Gen. Stephen Cheney, USMC (Ret.), President of American Security Project

The House Financial Services Subcommittee on National Security, International Development & Monetary Policy is holding a hearing right now on the macroeconomic impacts of climate change. Watch the hearing here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=51joZxKlKwc …

Because of climate change, places like Yellowstone have less water and higher temperatures. These hotter, drier conditions make wildfires far more likely. #SEECinYellowstone pic.twitter.com/GB3IFXTX48

From the geysers to the beetles and lodgepole pines, @YellowstoneNPS is the perfect laboratory to study the effects of climate change. The situation in America’s first national park shows that we must take action to mitigate those detrimental effects. #SEECinYellowstone pic.twitter.com/yeQmgyZd5k

Wildfires are a major problem around the world, from the Amazon to the Arctic. Here in Yellowstone and back in Washington state, there are more and more wildfires due to drier conditions brought about by climate change. #SEECinYellowstone pic.twitter.com/vhwmCGbkNv

Over the next couple days, I’ll be learning from park staff at Yellowstone about wildfires, invasive species, and reduced snowpack. We’ll discuss how these problems are affecting wildlife in the park, and how climate change is making them worse. #SEECinYellowstone
Just had a briefing from @YellowstoneNPS Superintendent Cam Sholly and lead climate scientist Ann Rodman on how climate change is affecting the park. pic.twitter.com/IAlgncUqAt
